{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563724"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:03:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:03:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16851"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16851"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.74,0.05,0.16,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9541"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67311"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9541"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16851"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52763"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1374"},{"type":"tags","id":"2451"},{"type":"tags","id":"4412"},{"type":"tags","id":"4434"},{"type":"tags","id":"12805"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22538"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67311"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman is admitted to the labour ward in active labour at 39 weeks gestation. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is receiving an oxytocin infusion for augmentation of labour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The midwife reports palpating five to six strong contractions every 10 minutes with minimal resting tone between contractions. The cardiotocograph shows a baseline fetal heart rate of 140 beats per minute with reduced baseline variability and no accelerations. The fetal heart rate suddenly drops to 80 beats per minute and remains at this level for five minutes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the fetal bradycardia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Uterine hyperstimulation","Placental abruption","Umbilical cord prolapse","Maternal hypotension","Uterine rupture"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes fetal bradycardia occurring in the context of excessive uterine activity during oxytocin augmentation of labour. \u003Cstrong\u003EUterine hyperstimulation\u003C/strong\u003E is defined as more than five contractions in 10 minutes, or contractions lasting longer than two minutes. The excessive frequency of contractions reduces the time available for placental perfusion between contractions, leading to fetal compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUterine rupture\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with sudden onset severe abdominal pain, vaginal bleeding, and loss of station of the presenting part. These features are not described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacental abruption\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with vaginal bleeding and severe constant abdominal pain. The pattern of uterine activity would not typically show frequent discrete contractions as described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUmbilical cord prolapse\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs with rupture of membranes and is associated with malpresentation or an unengaged presenting part. It would be visible on vaginal examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal hypotension\u003C/strong\u003E can cause reduced placental perfusion and subsequent fetal compromise, but there is no indication of maternal cardiovascular instability in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of uterine hyperstimulation includes immediate cessation of oxytocin, maternal positioning in left lateral, and consideration of tocolytic therapy if the bradycardia persists. Prevention involves careful titration of oxytocin and continuous CTG monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Uterine hyperstimulation is defined as more than 5 contractions in 10 minutes, or contractions lasting longer than 2 minutes.","Uterine hyperstimulation from oxytocin can cause fetal bradycardia due to reduced placental perfusion.","The first step in managing uterine hyperstimulation is to cease the oxytocin infusion."],"references":["Hope A. The fetal bradycardia. O\u0026G Magazine [Internet]. 2019 [cited 2024 Dec 4];19(2). Available from: https://www.ogmagazine.org.au/19/2-19/the-fetal-bradycardia/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52763"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16851"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52763"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T19:34:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T19:36:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9541"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67311"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description"